To create a TikZ diagram that visually represents the relations between different summation methods as described, we can use nodes to represent each summation method and arrows to indicate the relationships between them. Here's how you can generate the TikZ code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]

% Define nodes for each summation method
\node (A) {A};
\node (B) [below left of=A] {B};
\node (C) [below right of=B] {C};
\node (D) [below right of=A] {D};

% Draw arrows to represent the relationships
\draw[->] (A) -- node[above] {$a \to b$} (B);
\draw[<-] (B) -- node[below] {$b \twoheadrightarrow a$} (A);

\draw[->] (B) -- node[above] {$b \to c$} (C);
\draw[<-] (C) -- node[below] {$c \twoheadrightarrow b$} (B);

\draw[->] (A) -- node[above] {$a \to d$} (D);
\draw[<-] (D) -- node[below] {$d \twoheadrightarrow a$} (A);

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code will produce a diagram with four nodes labeled A, B, C, and D, representing different summation methods. Arrows are drawn between these nodes to show the relationships described in your prompt:
- An arrow from A to B labeled "$a \to b$" indicates that A-summation is a special case of B-summation.
- An arrow from B to A labeled "$b \twoheadrightarrow a$" indicates that if something is B-summable, it is also A-summable.

The same relationships are shown between B and C, and A and D. You can compile this LaTeX code using a LaTeX editor to see the resulting diagram.

